tive_disorders/miscellaneous/antibiotic_associated_colitis.xml" keywordId="63699" keywordSetId="28902" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/editorial/articles/health_and_medical_reference/digestive_disorders/miscellaneous/antibiotic_associated_colitis.xml">Clostridium difficile</a></i> (also called <i>C. difficile</i>) are bacteria
			 that can cause swelling and irritation of the
			 <a chronic_id="091e9c5e8001e8c1" directive="friendlyurl" document-type="MultiMedia" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/multimedia/large_intestine_multimedia_tp12580.xml" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/multimedia/large_intestine_multimedia_tp12580.xml">large intestine, or colon</a><a chronic_id="091e9c5e8001e8c1" directive="friendlyurl" document-type="MultiMedia" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/multimedia/large_intestine_multimedia_tp12580.xml" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/multimedia/large_intestine_multimedia_tp12580.xml"><img alt="camera.gif" border="0" height="13" src="/webmd/consumer_assets/site_images/media/interface/camera.gif" type="interface" width="22" directive="imageurl" chronic_id="091e9c5e80019c5c" object_type="wbmd_cons_img" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/site_images/media/interface/camera.gif"></a>. This
			 <a chronic_id="091e9c5e8001b4ec" directive="friendlyurl" document-type="Definition" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/definition/inflammation_definition_sti150782.xml" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/definition/inflammation_definition_sti150782.xml">inflammation</a>, known as <a chronic_id="" crossLinkId="31542" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="E0AA8DAA9FFF447A" href="http://www.webmd.com/ibd-crohns-disease/colitis-guide/ulcerative-colitis-overview-facts" keywordId="33400" keywordSetId="8455" object_type="" path="/webmdhttp://www.webmd.com/ibd-crohns-disease/colitis-guide/ulcerative-colitis-overview-facts">colitis</a>, can cause <a chronic_id="091e9c5e80007ea0" crossLinkId="5461" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e80007ea0" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/editorial/articles/health_and_medical_reference/digestive_disorders/miscellaneous/digestive_diseases_diarrhea.xml" keywordId="7253" keywordSetId="1090" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/editorial/articles/health_and_medical_reference/digestive_disorders/miscellaneous/digestive_diseases_diarrhea.xml">diarrhea</a>,
			 fever, and abdominal <a chronic_id="091e9c5e80612848" crossLinkId="1511127" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e80612848" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/editorial/articles/health_and_medical_reference/joints_bones_and_muscles/miscellaneous/muscle_spasms_cramps_and_charley_horse.xml" keywordId="73786" keywordSetId="28630" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/editorial/articles/health_and_medical_reference/joints_bones_and_muscles/miscellaneous/muscle_spasms_cramps_and_charley_horse.xml">cramps</a>.</p><p> You may get <a chronic_id="091e9c5e8001b3d0" directive="friendlyurl" document-type="Definition" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/definition/clostridium_difficile_colitis_definition_stp1995.xml" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/definition/clostridium_difficile_colitis_definition_stp1995.xml">C. difficile colitis<i>C. difficile</i></a> if you take
			 <a chronic_id="091e9c5e8001afd5" directive="friendlyurl" document-type="Definition" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/definition/antibiotics_definition_sta123268.xml" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/definition/antibiotics_definition_sta123268.xml">antibiotics</a>. <i>C. difficile</i> also
			 can be passed from person to person. But the infection is most common in people who
			 are taking antibiotics or have taken them recently. It is also common in older
			 people who are in hospitals and nursing homes and in people who are getting <a chronic_id="091e9c5e80d59ba7" crossLinkId="1577663" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e80d59ba7" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/editorial/articles/health_and_medical_reference/cancer/miscellaneous/chemotherapy_what_expect.xml" keywordId="74390" keywordSetId="33709" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/editorial/articles/health_and_medical_reference/cancer/miscellaneous/chemotherapy_what_expect.xml">chemotherapy</a> for <a chronic_id="" crossLinkId="31192" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="9A13E96B1FF14D08" href="http://www.webmd.com/cancer/" keywordId="7043" keywordSetId="942" object_type="" path="/webmdhttp://www.webmd.com/cancer/">cancer</a>.</p><p>Colitis caused by
			 <i>C. difficile</i> can be mild or serious. In rare cases, it
			 can cause death.</p></section_text></section_group><section_group><section_header>What causes it?</section_header><section_type>SpecialSection</section_type><section_text><p> The large intestine normally
			 contains many good bacteria that keep it healthy and do not cause disease. If
			 you take antibiotics to kill bacteria that do cause disease, your medicine may
			 also kill the good bacteria. This may allow <i>C. difficile</i>
			 bacteria to grow in your large intestine and release harmful substances called
			 toxins. Experts also think that, in some cases, antibiotics may cause these
			 toxins to be released.</p><p>When the toxins are released, the colon
			 becomes inflamed.</p><p>People who take medicines that reduce <a chronic_id="091e9c5e8035ee80" crossLinkId="70401" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e8035ee80" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/editorial/articles/image_collections/anatomy_pages/picture_of_the_stomach.xml" keywordId="58694" keywordSetId="25972" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/editorial/articles/image_collections/anatomy_pages/picture_of_the_stomach.xml">stomach</a> acid, such as <a chronic_id="" crossLinkId="31342" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="20536" href="http://www.webmd.com/drugs/drug-20536-Nexium+Oral.aspx?drugid=20536&amp;drugname=Nexium+Oral" keywordId="7958" keywordSetId="1616" object_type="" path="/webmdhttp://www.webmd.com/drugs/drug-20536-Nexium+Oral.aspx?drugid=20536&amp;drugname=Nexium+Oral">Nexium</a>, <a chronic_id="" crossLinkId="67677" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="9143" href="http://www.webmd.com/drugs/mono-9143-LANSOPRAZOLE+DELAYED-RELEASE+-+ORAL.aspx?drugid=11454&amp;drugname=Prevacid+Oral" keywordId="56151" keywordSetId="7806" object_type="" path="/webmdhttp://www.webmd.com/drugs/mono-9143-LANSOPRAZOLE+DELAYED-RELEASE+-+ORAL.aspx?drugid=11454&amp;drugname=Prevacid+Oral">Prevacid</a>, or <a chronic_id="" crossLinkId="67685" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="7957" href="http://www.webmd.com/drugs/drug-7957-prilosec+oral.aspx" keywordId="56159" keywordSetId="7807" object_type="" path="/webmdhttp://www.webmd.com/drugs/drug-7957-prilosec+oral.aspx">Prilosec</a>,  also have a greater risk of getting a <i>C. difficile</i> infection.<sup class="Reference"><a bookmark="abo4730" chronic_id="091e9c5e80299057" directive="friendlyurl" document-type="special" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/special/clostridium_difficile_colitis-references_special_uf6176spec-bib.xml" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/special/clostridium_difficile_colitis-references_special_uf6176spec-bib.xml">1</a></sup></p><p><i>C. difficile</i> may be spread when an infected person does not wash his or her hands after using the bathroom and then touches something like a door handle, bed rail, or phone. This may leave <i>C. difficile</i> bacteria on the objects. Other people can get infected if they touch a contaminated object and then eat or rub their faces with their hands. <a chronic_id="091e9c5e80d01476" crossLinkId="1559054" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e80d01476" href="/webmd/PageBuilder_Assets/scopemaps/WebMD Consumer/Pages/Health Care Reform A Guide to Health Insurance_091e9c5e80d01476/page_Health Care Reform A Guide to Health Insurance_091e9c5e80d01476.xml" keywordId="73363" keywordSetId="33248" object_type="wbmd_pb_page" path="/webmd/PageBuilder_Assets/scopemaps/WebMD Consumer/Pages/Health Care Reform A Guide to Health Insurance_091e9c5e80d01476/page_Health Care Reform A Guide to Health Insurance_091e9c5e80d01476.xml">Health care</a> workers can pass this bacteria from room to room in a hospital or a long-term care facility.</p><p>The best way to prevent spreading <i>C. difficile</i> is to <a chronic_id="091e9c5e8001d504" directive="friendlyurl" document-type="Special" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/special/hand-washing-topic_overview_special_tp21202.xml" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/special/hand-washing-topic_overview_special_tp21202.xml">wash your hands</a> often, especially after you use the bathroom. It is also a good idea to wash your hands before and after you visit a hospital, nursing home, or other place where people may be ill or weak.</p></section_text></section_group><section_group><section_header>What are the symptoms?</section_header><section_type>SpecialSection</section_type><section_text><p><i>C. difficile</i> colitis may cause:</p><ul><li>Diarrhea (may contain <a chronic_id="091e9c5e8056ea80" crossLinkId="1506783" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e8056ea80" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/editorial/articles/image_collections/anatomy_pages/anatomy_picture_of_blood.xml" keywordId="62987" keywordSetId="28544" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/editorial/articles/image_collections/anatomy_pages/anatomy_picture_of_blood.xml">blood</a> or pus).</li><li>Abdominal (belly) cramps.</li><li>Fever.</li><li><a chronic_id="091e9c5e8000b073" crossLinkId="900" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e8000b073" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/editorial/articles/health_and_medical_reference/miscellaneous/dehydration_adults.xml" keywordId="7238" keywordSetId="1077" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/editorial/articles/health_and_medical_reference/miscellaneous/dehydration_adults.xml">Dehydration</a>.</li></ul><p> You also may have an abnormal heartbeat.</p><p>Symptoms usually begin 4 to 10 days after you start taking antibiotics.
			 But they might not start until a few weeks after you stop taking
			 antibiotics.</p><p>The illness may be so mild that you have some
			 diarrhea but no fever or cramps. In rare cases, a person who is very ill may
			 develop a hole, or perforation, in the intestine. A perforation is a medical
			 emergency and requires surgery.</p></section_text></section_group></page><page><section_group><section_header>How is it diagnosed?</section_header><section_type>SpecialSection</section_type><section_text><p>Your doctor may think you
			 have <i>C. difficile</i> colitis if both of the following are true:</p><ul><li>You have symptoms of the illness.</li><li> You are taking, or you recently took, antibiotics.</li></ul><p>To confirm the diagnosis, a stool sample will be tested
			 to look for the toxins that <i>C. difficile</i> produces.</p><p>Your doctor may look at the colon through a lighted instrument
			 (<a chronic_id="091e9c5e8001af3b" directive="friendlyurl" document-type="Definition" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/definition/sigmoidoscopy_definition_tv7630.xml" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/definition/sigmoidoscopy_definition_tv7630.xml">sigmoidoscopy</a> or
			 <a chronic_id="091e9c5e8001b60b" directive="friendlyurl" document-type="Definition" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/definition/colonoscopy_definition_stc123734.xml" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/definition/colonoscopy_definition_stc123734.xml">colonoscopy</a>). In the most serious cases of
			 <i>C. difficile</i> colitis, patches of yellow and white tissue
			 may form on the inside of the colon.</p></section_text></section_group><section_group><section_header>How is it treated?</section_header><section_type>SpecialSection</section_type><section_text><p>First, if possible, your doctor will have you stop taking the antibiotic that caused the infection. Your doctor may then treat
			 <i>C. difficile</i> colitis with an antibiotic other than the one
			 that caused the infection. You will likely take fidaxomicin, <a chronic_id="" crossLinkId="31327" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="6426" href="http://www.webmd.com/drugs/drug-6426-Metronidazole+Oral.aspx?drugid=6426&amp;drugname=Metronidazole+Oral" keywordId="7895" keywordSetId="1570" object_type="" path="/webmdhttp://www.webmd.com/drugs/drug-6426-Metronidazole+Oral.aspx?drugid=6426&amp;drugname=Metronidazole+Oral">metronidazole</a>, or <a chronic_id="" crossLinkId="69443" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="8858" href="http://www.webmd.com/drugs/drug-8858-vancomycin+oral.aspx" keywordId="57920" keywordSetId="25435" object_type="" path="/webmdhttp://www.webmd.com/drugs/drug-8858-vancomycin+oral.aspx">vancomycin</a>. Sometimes the infection comes back a
			 few days after you stop treatment. If this happens, you may be given another
			 antibiotic.</p><p>If you have severe diarrhea, you also may be given fluids
			 to prevent
			 <a chronic_id="091e9c5e8001b063" directive="friendlyurl" document-type="Definition" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/definition/dehydration_definition_std120726.xml" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/definition/dehydration_definition_std120726.xml">dehydration</a> and to make sure you have the right amount
			 of minerals (<a chronic_id="" crossLinkId="64517" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="3399" href="http://www.webmd.com/drugs/drug-3399-oral+electrolytes+oral.aspx" keywordId="52996" keywordSetId="20606" object_type="" path="/webmdhttp://www.webmd.com/drugs/drug-3399-oral+electrolytes+oral.aspx">electrolytes</a>) in your blood. Or you may get a medicine called a bile salt binder (such as <a chronic_id="" crossLinkId="63526" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="4803" href="http://www.webmd.com/drugs/drug-4803-cholestyramine+light+oral.aspx" keywordId="52007" keywordSetId="19639" object_type="" path="/webmdhttp://www.webmd.com/drugs/drug-4803-cholestyramine+light+oral.aspx">cholestyramine</a>) that can help control the diarrhea.</p><p>For people who are not helped by antibiotics, a fecal transplant may be done. This treatment places stool from a donor into the colon of a person who has <i>C. difficile</i> infection. The good bacteria in the donor stool helps get rid of the <i>C. difficile</i> bacteria and restore health to the colon.<sup class="Reference"><a bookmark="abo4732" chronic_id="091e9c5e80299057" directive="friendlyurl" document-type="special" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/special/clostridium_difficile_colitis-references_special_uf6176spec-bib.xml" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/controlled_content/healthwise/special/clostridium_difficile_colitis-references_special_uf6176spec-bib.xml">2</a></sup></p><p>Probiotics, which are bacteria that help keep the natural balance of organisms (microflora) in the <a chronic_id="091e9c5e80390f7e" crossLinkId="70906" directive="friendlyurl" externalId="091e9c5e80390f7e" href="/webmd/consumer_assets/editorial/articles/image_collections/anatomy_pages/picture_of_the_intestines.xml" keywordId="60206" keywordSetId="26542" object_type="wbmd_cons_article" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/editorial/articles/image_collections/anatomy_pages/picture_of_the_intestines.xml">intestines</a>, may be helpful for people who have repeated <i>C. difficile</i> infections.</p><p>In rare cases, a person might need surgery to remove
			 part of the intestines. This would happen only if you did not get better with
			 antibiotics and you developed a perforation in your intestines.</p></section_text></section_group></page></pages><citations></citations><related_links_type></related_links_type><related_links_header></related_links_header><related_links_text></related_links_text></cons_import_health_ref></content_section></wbmd_asset></content><friendlyurls><target siteid="3" name="WebMD" issearchable="true" prefix="www" friendlyurl="/digestive-disorders/tc/clostridium-difficile-colitis-overview" owner="false"><breadcrumb><bread piece="Digestive Disorders Health Center" prefix="www" friendlyurl="/digestive-disorders/default.htm"></bread><bread piece="Digestive Disorders Related Topics" prefix="www" friendlyurl="/digestive-disorders/tc/default.htm"></bread></breadcrumb><centers><Topic id="994" name="tmg" chronicid="091e9c5e8001d41c" prefix="www" friendlyurl="/digestive-disorders/tc/clostridium-difficile-colitis-overview" type="Topic">Clostridium Difficile Colitis</Topic><Super id="1071" name="super center" chronicid="091e9c5e800252cc" prefix="www" friendlyurl="/digestive-disorders/default.htm" type="">Digestive Disorders</Super></centers></target><target siteid="8" name="WebMD_Mobile" issearchable="true" prefix="www" friendlyurl="/a-to-z-guides/tc/clostridium-difficile-colitis-overview" owner="false"><breadcrumb><bread piece="A to Z Guides" prefix="www" friendlyurl="/a-to-z-guides/default.htm"></bread><bread piece="Related Topics" prefix="www" friendlyurl="/a-to-z-guides/tc/default.htm"></bread></breadcrumb><centers><Topic id="11198" name="tmg" chronicid="091e9c5e8001d41c" prefix="www" friendlyurl="/a-to-z-guides/tc/clostridium-difficile-colitis-overview" type="Topic">Clostridium Difficile Colitis</Topic></centers></target></friendlyurls><referenced_objects><object chronic_id="091e9c5e80056718" thmbnl="" pointer="0" path="/webmd/consumer_assets/editorial/articles/health_and_medical_reference/digestive_disorders/miscellaneous/antibiotic_associated_colitis.wxml"><target siteid="3" 